WEBVTT

00:00:01.590 --> 00:00:06.270
PROFESSOR: Let us consider the
anharmonic oscillator, which

00:00:06.270 --> 00:00:11.940
means that you're taking the
unperturbed Hamiltonian to be

00:00:11.940 --> 00:00:13.710
the harmonic oscillator.

00:00:18.910 --> 00:00:22.600
And now, you want to
add an extra term that

00:00:22.600 --> 00:00:25.900
will make this anharmonic.

00:00:25.900 --> 00:00:31.300
Anharmonic reflects the fact
that the perturbations are

00:00:31.300 --> 00:00:35.200
oscillations of the system
are not exactly harmonic.

00:00:35.200 --> 00:00:39.190
And in the harmonic oscillator,
the energy difference

00:00:39.190 --> 00:00:42.374
between levels is
always the same.

00:00:42.374 --> 00:00:45.240
That's a beautiful property
of the harmonic oscillator.

00:00:45.240 --> 00:00:49.140
That stops happening in
an anharmonic oscillator.

00:00:49.140 --> 00:00:51.150
The energy differences can vary.

00:00:51.150 --> 00:00:56.490
So the things, if you have
a transition from one level,

00:00:56.490 --> 00:01:00.090
first level to the ground state,
or second level to the ground

00:01:00.090 --> 00:01:03.450
state, one is not the
harmonic of the other

00:01:03.450 --> 00:01:09.740
because they're not exactly
twice as big as each other.

00:01:09.740 --> 00:01:19.280
So let's try to add an x to
the 4th perturbation, which

00:01:19.280 --> 00:01:21.320
is intuitively very clear.

00:01:21.320 --> 00:01:24.840
You have a potential.

00:01:24.840 --> 00:01:27.870
And you're adding
now an extra piece

00:01:27.870 --> 00:01:30.960
that behaves like x to the 4th.

00:01:30.960 --> 00:01:35.310
And it's going to make this
potential blow up faster.

00:01:38.380 --> 00:01:40.600
Now, in order to
get the units right,

00:01:40.600 --> 00:01:43.280
we need the length scale.

00:01:43.280 --> 00:01:53.080
There's a length scale d
in the harmonic oscillator.

00:01:53.080 --> 00:01:56.050
We're going to use it.

00:01:56.050 --> 00:01:58.360
One way to derive
that length scale is

00:01:58.360 --> 00:02:04.210
to recall from units that p,
a momentum, has units of h

00:02:04.210 --> 00:02:05.530
divided by length.

00:02:05.530 --> 00:02:09.789
So b squared has units of
h squared over d squared.

00:02:09.789 --> 00:02:10.870
There's an m.

00:02:10.870 --> 00:02:13.640
So that's an energy.

00:02:13.640 --> 00:02:15.610
And this is an energy too.

00:02:15.610 --> 00:02:22.100
So we can set it equal to
m omega squared d squared.

00:02:22.100 --> 00:02:28.850
From where we get, for
example, as 1 over d to the 4th

00:02:28.850 --> 00:02:36.890
is equal to m squared omega
squared over h squared.

00:02:36.890 --> 00:02:43.630
And d squared is equal
to h over m omega.

00:02:43.630 --> 00:02:46.060
So that's a length
scale, something

00:02:46.060 --> 00:02:50.960
with units of length in
the harmonic oscillator.

00:02:50.960 --> 00:02:53.700
So if we want to add
the perturbation that

00:02:53.700 --> 00:02:57.640
is x to the 4th, we'll
add a lambda delta

00:02:57.640 --> 00:03:01.030
H that is going to
be a lambda, which

00:03:01.030 --> 00:03:04.070
is unit freedom, something
that has units of energy.

00:03:04.070 --> 00:03:08.710
So you can put h bar
mega has units of energy.

00:03:08.710 --> 00:03:11.410
And then you can
put the operator x

00:03:11.410 --> 00:03:14.860
to the 4th divided
by d to the 4th.

00:03:20.810 --> 00:03:23.310
It's a perturbation
with units of energy.

00:03:23.310 --> 00:03:23.900
This is good.

00:03:27.370 --> 00:03:34.570
So there's a couple of
ways of thinking of it.

00:03:34.570 --> 00:03:38.560
You may remember that in
the harmonic oscillator

00:03:38.560 --> 00:03:45.070
x, the operator x, was given
by the square root of h

00:03:45.070 --> 00:03:49.855
over 2m omega, a plus a dagger.

00:03:52.360 --> 00:04:06.450
So this is d times a plus a
dagger over square root of 2.

00:04:11.480 --> 00:04:19.790
So this perturbation lambda
delta H is equal to lambda.

00:04:19.790 --> 00:04:21.769
H bar omega would be here.

00:04:21.769 --> 00:04:24.050
H bar omega.

00:04:24.050 --> 00:04:32.210
Now x/d is this a plus a dagger
divided by square root of 2.

00:04:32.210 --> 00:04:39.750
So you have a 4a plus
a dagger to the 4th.

00:04:39.750 --> 00:04:47.060
So that's lambda delta H.
That's your perturbation.

00:04:54.730 --> 00:04:57.830
So what do we want to do
with this perturbation?

00:04:57.830 --> 00:04:59.710
It's a nice perturbation.

00:04:59.710 --> 00:05:01.840
We want to compute
the corrections

00:05:01.840 --> 00:05:05.290
to the energy,
corrections to the states,

00:05:05.290 --> 00:05:07.075
and see how they go.

00:05:09.990 --> 00:05:11.115
We can do that easily.

00:05:18.410 --> 00:05:21.340
Let's compute first that
corrections to the ground state

00:05:21.340 --> 00:05:24.080
energy.

00:05:24.080 --> 00:05:27.340
These are calculations
that are not difficult,

00:05:27.340 --> 00:05:31.440
but they take some care.

00:05:31.440 --> 00:05:34.900
As any calculation,
